			<div class="article-correspondence layout-item fill-pattern-light">
		<div class="layout-item-intro">
			<h2>Correspondence</h2>
			<a class="xsmall link-alt" href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">Write a Letter to the Editor&nbsp;&#9656;</a>
		</div>

		<div id="article-correspondences" class="correspondences correspondences-collapsed">
								<div class="block-correspondence" id="1110">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>David James Duncan&rsquo;s disturbing dream [&ldquo;<a href="/article/770">meeting with a god</a>,&rdquo; December 2000] appeared to reflect his frustration with trying to educate politicians and government agencies in the environmental perspective. I hope he will keep at it, though, and not become discouraged. Look what running water does to rock over time.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Lynn Regudon<br>Edmonds, Washington</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="1111">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>I disagree with David James Duncan that &ldquo;there is a faith called fishing.&rdquo; Fishing is just another cruel pastime. Does Duncan really believe that his catch-and-release policy makes him a &ldquo;sportsman&rdquo;? I have a hunch that swallowing a titanium hook probably hurts like hell.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Travis Kirchner<br>El Paso, Texas</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence-respond fill-pattern-light" id="1112">
								<p><a href="/contributors/david-james-duncan"><strong>David James Duncan</strong></a> responds:</p>
							<p>If the cells of our bodies, synapses of our minds, and beats of our hearts are the product of any one method of manufacture I can name, I&rsquo;d call that method &ldquo;sacrifice&rdquo;: hooks, arrows, spears, crosses, self-starvation under bo trees in the name of truth, blood, pain, death, and all the rest. Life is a Eucharist feast, and, as Meister Eckhart says, &ldquo;Love is like a fisherman&rsquo;s hook.&rdquo; We&rsquo;re born in blood and pain. We can&rsquo;t escape it. But we <em>can</em> be mindful, frugal, grateful, and willing to make sacrifices ourselves. The faith called fishing helps some of us to do this. If you don&rsquo;t believe it&rsquo;s a faith, great: I won&rsquo;t see you on my river!</p>
	</div>


					</div>

